+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HeRrmJyEeBMKJfXCQibEiG","type":"tool_result","content":"import { EventBus } from '../events/bus.js';\nimport { ORDER_EVENTS, OrderCreatedEvent, OrderCancelledEvent } from '../events/types.js';\nimport { InventoryRepository } from './repository.js';\n\nexport class InventoryService {\n  constructor(\n    private repo: InventoryRepository,\n    private eventBus: EventBus\n  ) {}\n\n  registerHandlers(): void {\n    this.eventBus.on(ORDER_EVENTS.CREATED, this.handleOrderCreated.bind(this));\n    this.eventBus.on(ORDER_EVENTS.CANCELLED, this.handleOrderCancelled.bind(this));\n  }\n\n  private async handleOrderCreated(data: unknown): Promise<void> {\n    const event = data as OrderCreatedEvent;\n    const reservations: Array<{ productId: string; quantity: number }> = [];\n\n    for (const item of event.items) {\n      const success = this.repo.reserve(item.productId, item.quantity);\n      if (!success) {\n        // Rollback previous reservations\n        for (const res of reservations) {\n          this.repo.release(res.productId, res.quantity);\n        }\n        throw new Error(\n          `Insufficient stock for product ${item.productId}`\n        );\n      }\n      reservations.push({ productId: item.productId, quantity: item.quantity });\n    }\n\n    await this.eventBus.emit(ORDER_EVENTS.STOCK_RESERVED, {\n      orderId: event.orderId,\n      items: reservations,\n      timestamp: Date.now(),\n    });\n  }\n\n  private async handleOrderCancelled(data: unknown): Promise<void> {\n    const event = data as OrderCancelledEvent;\n    // Release reserved stock — look up original order items from the event\n    // The order service attaches items to the cancellation event\n    const eventWithItems = data as OrderCancelledEvent & {\n      items?: Array<{ productId: string; quantity: number }>;\n      status?: string;\n    };\n\n    if (eventWithItems.status !== 'cancelled') return;\n\n    if (eventWithItems.items) {\n      for (const item of eventWithItems.items) {\n        this.repo.release(item.productId, item.quantity);\n      }\n    }\n\n    await this.eventBus.emit(ORDER_EVENTS.STOCK_RELEASED, {\n      orderId: event.orderId,\n      timestamp: Date.now(),\n    });\n  }\n\n  setStock(productId: string, quantity: number): void {\n    this.repo.setStock(productId, quantity);\n  }\n\n  getStock(productId: string) {\n    return this.repo.getStock(productId);\n  }\n}","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01KLKhkr3rcaS5yAt84yhMtV","session_id":"dcea4a68-cf7c-47d3-960b-ad9e22c63ec8","uuid":"584e5423-09a9-4169-a778-1bf7cb3f332e"}
+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KLKhkr3rcaS5yAt84yhMtV","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of all six bugs, the original code, the planted bugs, and the fixes. Let me compile the review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: 6 Bug Fixes in Event-Driven Order Processing System\n\n### Summary\n\nAll 34 tests pass, TypeScript compilation succeeds, and each of the six fixes addresses a genuine defect. Five of the six fixes are correct and faithfully restore the intended behavior. One fix area (bugs 5 and 6 together) involves a subtle design choice that merits closer examination. Overall the work is solid.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 1: `src/orders/repository.ts` -- Spread existing record before updates\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/orders/repository.ts`, line 38\n\n**Bug:** The `update()` method was constructed as `{ ...updates, id, updatedAt }`, discarding all fields from the existing record that were not included in the partial `updates` object. This meant that updating a single field (e.g., `status`) would wipe out `customerId`, `items`, `total`, `notes`, etc.\n\n**Fix applied:**\n```typescript\nconst updated = { ...existing, ...updates, id, updatedAt: Date.now() } as Order;\n```\n\n**Assessment: Correct.** This is a textbook spread-merge pattern for partial updates. The `id` is placed last to prevent callers from accidentally changing it, which is good defensive practice. The `as Order` cast is acceptable here since the merge of a full `Order` with a `Partial<Order>` produces an `Order`.\n\n**Verdict:** No issues.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 2: `src/events/bus.ts` -- Instance-level handler registry\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/events/bus.ts`, lines 3-29\n\n**Bug:** The handler registry was a module-level `Map` (`globalHandlers`) shared across all `EventBus` instances. This caused handler leakage between tests and between logically independent bus instances.\n\n**Fix applied:** Moved the handlers `Map` to a `private` instance property:\n```typescript\nexport class EventBus {\n  private handlers: Map<string, EventHandler[]> = new Map();\n  // ... all methods now reference this.handlers instead of globalHandlers\n}\n```\n\n**Assessment: Correct.** The fix properly scopes handler state to each `EventBus` instance. The test setup creates a fresh `EventBus` in each `beforeEach`, which now correctly isolates handlers between tests. The `clear()` method still works as expected for cleanup within a single instance.\n\n**Verdict:** No issues. This is a clean, minimal change.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 3: `src/billing/calculator.ts` -- Remove intermediate rounding\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/billing/calculator.ts`, lines 20-29\n\n**Bug:** Each intermediate calculation (`discountAmount`, `afterDiscount`, `taxAmount`) was individually rounded to 2 decimal places, but the final `total` was NOT rounded. This double-rounding of intermediates could cause penny-level drift, and the unrounded `total` could return values like `130.8600000000001`.\n\n**Fix applied:**\n```typescript\nconst discountAmount = subtotal * (discountPercent / 100);\nconst afterDiscount = subtotal - discountAmount;\nconst taxAmount = afterDiscount * taxRate;\nconst total = afterDiscount + taxAmount;\n\nreturn {\n  subtotal: Math.round(subtotal * 100) / 100,\n  discountAmount: Math.round(discountAmount * 100) / 100,\n  taxAmount: Math.round(taxAmount * 100) / 100,\n  total: Math.round(total * 100) / 100,\n};\n```\n\n**Assessment: Correct.** The fix computes full-precision intermediates and only rounds at the output boundary. This is the standard approach for financial calculations in floating-point arithmetic (short of using a decimal library). The test at line 46-59 in `/workspace/tests/billing.test.ts` (\"rounds correctly for penny-edge amounts\") specifically validates this behavior with a case that would fail under double-rounding.\n\n**One observation:** The returned `subtotal`, `discountAmount`, and `taxAmount` are each independently rounded, so `discountAmount + afterDiscount` will not necessarily equal `subtotal` due to their independent rounding. For display purposes this is fine. If you ever need strict accounting equality (`subtotal - discountAmount + taxAmount == total`), you would need to derive the displayed amounts differently. This is not a bug in the current system, just something to be aware of if the breakdown is ever used for ledger entries.\n\n**Verdict:** No issues for current usage.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 4: `src/billing/service.ts` -- Added `.bind(this)` to `handleRefund`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/billing/service.ts`, line 25\n\n**Bug:** The `handleRefund` method was registered as `this.handleRefund` without `.bind(this)`, causing `this` to be `undefined` when the event bus invokes it. This would crash at `this.payments.get(...)` and `this.notificationService.sendRefundNotice(...)`.\n\n**Fix applied:**\n```typescript\nthis.eventBus.on(ORDER_EVENTS.REFUNDED, this.handleRefund.bind(this));\n```\n\n**Assessment: Correct.** This is consistent with the `handleStockReserved` registration on the line immediately above, which already used `.bind(this)`. The test at `/workspace/tests/billing.test.ts` lines 113-126 (\"sends refund notification\") exercises this path end-to-end.\n\n**Suggestion (non-blocking):** To prevent this class of bug from recurring, consider declaring handlers as arrow-function class fields:\n```typescript\nprivate handleRefund = async (data: unknown): Promise<void> => { ... };\n```\nArrow fields capture `this` lexically, eliminating the need to remember `.bind(this)` at registration. This is a style preference and not required.\n\n**Verdict:** No issues.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 5: `src/inventory/service.ts` -- Removed bogus status check\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/inventory/service.ts`, lines 50-53 (current), originally lines 50-52 (with the guard)\n\n**Bug:** The `handleOrderCancelled` handler had a guard `if (eventWithItems.status !== 'cancelled') return;` that checked for a `status` field on the event payload. This was a planted bug because the original code (commit `0984c00`) DID include `status: 'cancelled'` in the emitted event AND had this guard -- so the guard worked.\n\n**What the bug-planting commit did:** It removed `status: 'cancelled'` from the emitted cancellation event in `src/orders/service.ts` AND removed the `this.repo.update(id, { status: 'cancelled' })` call from BEFORE the emit to AFTER the emit. This meant the guard in the inventory service would never see `status === 'cancelled'` and would silently return without releasing stock.\n\n**Fix applied:** The fix removed the `status` guard in the inventory service. The fix did NOT restore `status: 'cancelled'` to the emitted event, nor did it restore the original ordering (update-then-emit).\n\n**Assessment: Functionally correct, but diverges from the original design.** Let me elaborate:\n\nIn the original code (`0984c00`), `cancelOrder` followed this sequence:\n1. Update order status to 'cancelled' in the repository\n2. Emit the CANCELLED event (with `status: 'cancelled'` in the payload)\n\nThe current fix follows this sequence:\n1. Emit the CANCELLED event (without `status` in the payload)\n2. Update order status to 'cancelled' in the repository\n\nBoth approaches work for the current tests. However, the original design (update-then-emit) had a meaningful intent: if any event handler queries the order repository during event processing, it should see the order already in 'cancelled' status. The current emit-then-update ordering means that during cancellation event processing, a handler querying the order repo would still see `status: 'confirmed'`.\n\nThis is not causing test failures because no current handler queries the order repository during `ORDER_EVENTS.CANCELLED` processing -- the inventory service only looks at the event payload. But it is a latent concern for future handlers.\n\nThe `status` property is still declared in the type widening at line 47 (`status?: string`) but is now vestigial since nothing sets it and nothing checks it. This is dead code.\n\n**Verdict:** The fix works and all tests pass. However, the implementation does not fully match the original design intent. This is a **low-risk** divergence but should be noted.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider one of two cleanup paths:\n- (A) Restore the original ordering: update status before emit, and include `status` in the event payload. This is what the original code did.\n- (B) Keep the current approach but remove the dead `status?: string` type extension at line 47, since it is no longer used.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 6: `src/orders/service.ts` -- Changed `>=` to `>` for 30-day refund boundary\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/orders/service.ts`, line 99\n\n**Bug:** The refund window check used `>=`, rejecting refunds on exactly day 30. Since `REFUND_WINDOW_DAYS = 30` and the business intent is a \"30-day refund window,\" orders created exactly 30 days ago should still be eligible for refund.\n\n**Fix applied:**\n```typescript\nif (daysSinceCreation > REFUND_WINDOW_DAYS) {\n```\n\n**Assessment: Correct.** The test \"allows refund on exactly day 30\" at `/workspace/tests/orders.test.ts` lines 93-104 validates the boundary condition, and the test \"rejects refund after 30-day window\" at lines 106-116 validates that day 31 is rejected. The `Math.floor` on the day calculation means that the window is effectively \"up to and including the 30th calendar day,\" which is standard for consumer refund policies.\n\n**Verdict:** No issues.\n\n---\n\n### Cross-Cutting Observations\n\n**Test Coverage:** The 34 tests provide good coverage of the happy paths and important edge cases. The boundary condition test for the 30-day refund (Fix 6) and the penny-edge rounding test (Fix 3) are particularly well-targeted. There are a few areas where additional tests could strengthen confidence:\n\n- **Suggestion:** A test that creates two separate `EventBus` instances and verifies handler isolation would directly regression-test Fix 2. The current tests indirectly cover this through `beforeEach` isolation, but a direct test would be more explicit.\n- **Suggestion:** A test that exercises the full create-cancel-refund lifecycle and verifies the refund notification message content would cover the end-to-end path through Fix 4.\n\n**Type Safety:** The event system uses `unknown` for event data and relies on `as` casts throughout handlers (e.g., `data as OrderCancelledEvent`). This is a known pattern tradeoff in TypeScript event systems. It is not introduced by these fixes, but is worth noting as a general improvement area if the system grows.\n\n**Dead Code from Fix 5:** As noted above, the `status?: string` type extension at `/workspace/src/inventory/service.ts` line 47 is now dead code. The `eventWithItems` variable on line 45 is also a redundant re-cast of `data`, since `event` (line 42) already has the needed type and the widened type only adds the now-unused `status`.\n\n---\n\n### Issue Summary\n\n| # | Severity | File | Issue |\n|---|----------|------|-------|\n| 1 | **Suggestion** | `/workspace/src/orders/service.ts` | Consider restoring update-before-emit ordering in `cancelOrder` to match original design intent |\n| 2 | **Suggestion** | `/workspace/src/inventory/service.ts` | Remove dead `status?: string` type extension and redundant `eventWithItems` re-cast (lines 45-48) |\n| 3 | **Suggestion** | `/workspace/src/billing/service.ts` | Consider using arrow-function class fields for event handlers to prevent future `.bind(this)` omissions |\n\nAll six fixes are functionally correct. The tests pass, the build compiles cleanly, and the code quality is consistent with the rest of the codebase. The only item that warrants a closer look is the ordering change in `cancelOrder` (Fix 5), which is a design-level divergence from the original code rather than a correctness problem."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ad8aa0e (for resumi